You can ensure that only one thread accesses the database at a time by using a [`SemaphoreSlim`][1]. To avoid repeating the try/finally block on every DB call, you could wrap in inside a generic method like the one bellow:

    private static readonly SemaphoreSlim _dbSemaphore = new SemaphoreSlim(1);

    public static Task&lt;TResult&gt; DBCall&lt;TResult&gt;(Func&lt;TResult&gt; function)
    {
        return Task.Run(async () =&gt;
        {
            await _dbSemaphore.WaitAsync().ConfigureAwait(false);
            try
            {
                return function();
            }
            finally
            {
                _dbSemaphore.Release();
            }
        });
    }

Then you could safely call the database, having the option to await each call or not:

    var result = await DBCall(() =&gt; (int)cmd.ExecuteScalar()); // Awaited
    _ = DBCall(() =&gt; cmd.ExecuteNonQuery()); // Not awaited

Another idea is to go one step further, and limit all database access to a single dedicated thread. I am not sure if this offers any tangible advantages, but seems a bit tidier and possibly safer as well. To achieve this you could consider implementing a custom [`TaskScheduler`][2] that queues tasks to a long-running thread:

    public class SingleThreadTaskScheduler : TaskScheduler, IDisposable
    {
        private readonly BlockingCollection&lt;Task&gt; _blockingCollection;

        public SingleThreadTaskScheduler()
        {
            _blockingCollection = new BlockingCollection&lt;Task&gt;();
            var thread = new Thread(() =&gt;
            {
                foreach (var task in _blockingCollection.GetConsumingEnumerable())
                {
                    task.Wait(); // Causes the execution of TryExecuteTaskInline
                }
            })
            { IsBackground = true };
            thread.Start();
        }

        public override int MaximumConcurrencyLevel =&gt; 1;

        protected override void QueueTask(Task task) =&gt; _blockingCollection.Add(task);

        protected override bool TryExecuteTaskInline(Task task,
            bool taskWasPreviouslyQueued) =&gt; return TryExecuteTask(task);

        protected override IEnumerable&lt;Task&gt; GetScheduledTasks() =&gt; _blockingCollection;

        public void Dispose() =&gt; _blockingCollection.CompleteAdding();
    }

This class may need some review. I am not 100% sure about its correctness. A quote from the documentation of the method [`TryExecuteTaskInline`][3]:

&gt; If a scheduler uses a dedicated thread to execute tasks, any inlining requests from that thread should succeed.  

The `DBCall` method can then make use of the custom `TaskScheduler` like this:

    private static SingleThreadTaskScheduler stts = new SingleThreadTaskScheduler();

    public static Task&lt;TResult&gt; DBCall&lt;TResult&gt;(Func&lt;TResult&gt; function)
    {
        return Task.Factory.StartNew(() =&gt;
        {
            return function();
        }, CancellationToken.None, TaskCreationOptions.None, stts);
    }

No locking mechanism is required. The exclusiveness is guaranteed by the task scheduler.

A missing feature is some mechanism for waiting the completion of the queued tasks before closing the program. Background threads are aborted when a .NET application exits.

  [1]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.threading.semaphoreslim
  [2]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.threading.tasks.taskscheduler
  [3]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.threading.tasks.taskscheduler.tryexecutetaskinline

